gland","Aldwark, Yorkshire, England":"Aldwark, Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Old Malton, Yorkshire, England":"Old Malton, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thirkell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name; according to   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames  , the modern Yorks and Durham name is probably not from the name in (2) but a metathesized variant of   Threlkeld  . The connection is unambiguous in Lancelot Threlkelde, 1472 in   Yorks Deeds   (Londesborough, ER Yorks), and Christopher Thirkylde, 1556, Elizabeth Therkall, 1608 in   York Registry Wills   (Goodmanham, ER Yorks). Later examples include Thomas Thirkell, 1624, Thomasine Threlkeld, 1673 in   IGI   (Brancepeth, Durham); John Thirkeld, 1741, Dorothy Threlkeld, 1755 in   IGI   (Morpeth, Northumb); John Threlkeld, 1776, James Thirkell, 1822 in   IGI   (Kirkby Fleetham, NR Yorks).","2  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>T(h)irkill</i>,  <i>T(h)urkill</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>Þorkell</i>,  <i>Thorkil</i>,  <i>Thurkil</i>, a contracted form of  <i>Þorketill</i>).  Compare  Thirkettle  . If the NR Yorks family name, cited in several examples below, survived into the modern period, it will have been confused with and absorbed by (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Thirtle","meanings":["English: variant of   Thirkell   with late dissimilation of  <i>kl</i> to  <i>tl</i>."]},{"name":"Turtle","meanings":["English:","variant of   Turkel   2.","nickname from Middle English <i>turtel</i>, <i>turtle</i> ‘turtle dove’ (Old English <i>turtle</i>, <i>turtla</i>)."]},{"name":"Tuttle","meanings":["English (Norfolk, Suffolk and Berkshire):","possibly a variant of <b>Thirkell</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)irkill</i>, <i>T(h)urkill</i> (Old Norse <i>Thorkell</i>, <i>Thorkil</i>, <i>Thurkil</i>, a shortened form of <i>Thorketill</i> from the god's name <i>Thórr</i> ‘Thor’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘kettle, cauldron’).","variant of   Tuthill  ."]},{"name":"Thirkhill","meanings":["English:  see  Thirkell  ."]},{"name":"Thurtle","meanings":["English: variant of   Thirkell   with late dissimilation of  <i>kl</i> to  <i>tl</i>."]},{"name":"Turtill","meanings":["English:  see  Turtle  ."]},{"name":"Thurkle","meanings":["English:  see  Thirkell  ."]},{"name":"Thirkill","meanings":["English:  see  Thirkell  ."]},{"name":"Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Wat</i>, a pet form of  <i>Walter</i>, and Middle English  <i>maugh</i>,  <i>mough</i> ‘kinsman by marriage, brother-in-law, son-in-law’.  See  Mowe   (1), and compare Robert Waltersmaghe, 1305 in   Black  . In origin it was mainly a Lancs surname, that spread eastwards and southwards in post-medieval times.   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes that in 1634 Joshua Watmough of London granted land to a man from Bradford (WR Yorks), and was described as ‘a younger son of Hugh Watmough late of Bury’ (Lancs)."]},{"name":"Thurtell","meanings":["English: variant of   Thirkell   with late dissimilation of  <i>kl</i> to  <i>tl</i>."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Thirkell was born about 1325, in York, Yorkshire, England, her father, Thomas Thirkell, was 17 and her mother, Alice Drakelowe, was 14. She had at least 3 daughters with John de Barden. She died about 1374, in Old Malton, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1325–about 1374":"umbes 1325–umbes 1374","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1329–1378":"1329–1378","1346–1403":"1346–1403","1363–Female":"1363–Surnud","1370–1440":"1370–1440","1310–1369":"1310–1369","1312–1420":"1312–1420","1440":"1440","1363":"1363","1374":"1374","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1403":"1403","1369":"1369","1325":"1325","1346":"1346","ABT 1363":"umbes 1363","1334":"1334","1312":"1312","1378":"1378","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1310":"1310","about 1346":"umbes 1346","about 1374":"umbes 1374","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Aldwark, Yorkshire, England":"Aldwark, Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Old Malton, Yorkshire, England":"Old Malton, Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1325–about 1374":"noin 1325–noin 1374","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1329–1378":"1329–1378","1346–1403":